{"key":"post-16413084","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>16413084</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;Terry M said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Question for RR:&lt;br /&gt;Can the Fischer hygrometers be left in a high humidity environment (95%) all the time, or should they just be put in for 5 minutes or so to get a reading in order to protect them and extend their lives?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I haven't removed either of mine from the grow room since day one.&amp;nbsp; We spray twice daily with a hose, and while we try to avoid direct high pressure spray on the hygrometers, plenty of water splashes directly on the units every time with no harm. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;For most commercial mushrooms, you don't really want to maintain a very high humidity all the time.&amp;nbsp; Spray well, which is going to raise the humidity up to 98% or so, and then let it drop to 75%(or lower if growing strictly shiitake) and then spray again.&amp;nbsp; This benefits whatever you're growing and as an added benefit, lets the hygrometer dry out inside and&amp;nbsp; keeps the mechanism constantly moving.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>16413274</next>\n<prev>16413076</prev>\n<first>16400345</first>\n<last>16485676</last>\n<when>1340286833</when>\n<utime>06/21/12 04:53 PM</utime>\n</post>"}